## ✅ Lesson 10 — Role-Based APIs (Very Important for HPM Support Tool)

In your **Philips Hospital Patient Monitoring Support Tool**, the application is **role-based**.

That means:

* Different users see different UI
* Different users call different APIs
* Same API returns different data
* Some APIs allowed only for specific roles

So QA must test **Role-Based API behavior**.

This lesson is very important for your project.

---

## 🔹 1. What is Role-Based API

Role-based API means:

> API response depends on user role

Example roles in your project:

* Normal User
* R&D
* Medic / Clinical
* Field Service Engineer (FSE)
* Admin

Same API → different response.

---

## 🔹 2. Real Flow in HPM Support Tool

Login:

```
POST /login
```

Response:

```
token + role
```

Next API:

```
GET /features
Authorization: Bearer token
```

Backend checks role → sends features.

Flow:

```
Login → token → role → header → API → response based on role
```

---

## 🔹 3. Example — Features API

API:

```
GET /api/features
```

### Normal user

Response:

```json
{
  "role": "USER",
  "features": ["dashboard"]
}
```

### FSE

```json
{
  "role": "FSE",
  "features": ["enumerator","connect","logs"]
}
```

### Admin

```json
{
  "role": "ADMIN",
  "features": ["enumerator","connect","logs","config","users"]
}
```

Same API
Different JSON

QA must test this.

---

## 🔹 4. Example — Enumerator API (Real scenario)

Enumerator should work only for FSE / Admin.

API:

```
GET /enumerator
```

Normal user:

```
403 Forbidden
```

FSE:

```
200 OK
```

Admin:

```
200 OK
```

QA must validate permission.

This is very common in Philips tools.

